    <subfield code="a">We prove that a nonempty closed and geodesically convex subset of the <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>∞</mo></mrow></msub></math> plane <math altimg="si153.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msubsup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>∞</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></math> is hyperconvex and we characterize the tight spans of arbitrary subsets of <math altimg="si153.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msubsup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>∞</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></math> via this property: Given any nonempty <math altimg="si3.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>X</mi><mo>⊆</mo><msubsup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>∞</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></math> , a closed, geodesically convex and minimal subset <math altimg="si4.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>Y</mi><mo>⊆</mo><msubsup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>∞</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></math> containing X is isometric to the tight span <math altimg="si42.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>T</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> of X .</subfield>
